    "recap_headline": "University of Pittsburgh Athletics",
    "recap_text": "STANFORD, CA \u2013\nThe Pitt Panthers (14-4, 2-1 ACC) ended the weekend with two-straight wins over Stanford (7-12, 1-5 ACC) to clinch their first ACC series of the season.\nDespite falling in the series opener, the Panthers roared back with two road wins to take the series. It's the first time that Pitt has won their first ACC series of the year since 2021.\nEddie Smink\nearned his first win of the season, throwing 5.1 stellar innings in relief for the Panthers. Smink surrendered just five hits and did not allow a single walk in his outing. When Pitt needed a steady presence on the mound, Smink delivered and kept the Cardinal bats at bay for the remainder of the afternoon. The Panthers rode him from the bottom of the fourth inning until the final out in the ninth.\nLorenzo Carrier\nreached in all six of his plate appearances on Sunday, going 4-4 with three runs scored, two walks, a double and an RBI. He is now hitting .516 and slugging 1.145 with 32 hits, 28 runs and 43 RBI this season.\nCaden Dulin\nlogged his first three-hit game of the season in the win, going 3-5 with two runs scored. Third baseman\nKai Wagner\nknocked in runs on each of his hits as he had a season-high three RBI.\nAJ Nessler\ncontinues to get on base with another multiple-hit game this season. Nessler scored and drove in a run in his 11\nth\nmulti-hit game of the year.\nKai Wagner\ngot the scoring started on Sunday with a two-run double in the top of the first inning.\nCaden Dulin\nlined a one-out single to left and moved up to third on a\nLorenzo Carrier\ndouble in the following at-bat. With two runners in scoring position, Wagner roped a double into the right center gap to give the Panthers a two-run lead in the first. Pitt scored first in all three games this weekend.\nWhile Stanford tied the game up on a two-run home run in the bottom half of the inning, the Panthers responded with a four-run top of the second.\nIn his first at-bat since his go-ahead home run in Saturday's game two,\nCarter Dierdorf\nled off the second inning with a single to left. After\nJulian Irizarry\nreached on an error in the following at-bat, both he and Dierdorf moved up 90 feet on a balk.\nAJ Nessler\nwould then drive in Dierdorf from third on an RBI groundout to put the Panthers back in front. Pitt took advantage of another Stanford balk as Irizarry trotted home on the second balk of the inning by the Cardinal pitcher.\nKai Wagner\ndrove in his third run of the game on a single to right center and\nTrey Fenderson\nlined an RBI double off the third base bag to extend the Panther lead to four.\nStanford plated two more on another two-run home run in the bottom of the second inning and the Panthers led 6-4 through two.\nPitt extended their lead to four with a pair of runs in the top of the fifth inning.\nCarter Dierdorf\ndrove in\nSebastian Pisacreta\non a single to center after Pisacreta led off the inning with the first triple of his career. With runners on first and second,\nLorenzo Carrier\ndrove in Pitt's eighth run of the day on an RBI single to right. They led 8-4 after five innings.\nThe Panthers and Cardinal exchanged runs in the sixth and seventh innings as Pitt's four-run lead stayed put through seven innings.\nLorenzo Carrier\ngot the Panther offense going in top of the seventh with his fourth hit of the game. Two walks in the following at-bats loaded the bases with two outs. Carrier dashed home on a wild pitch to extend Pitt's lead back to four.\nThe Panthers added insurance in the top of the ninth inning, extending their lead to five.\nSebastian Pisacreta\nsingled to left center with two outs and would score two at-bats later on a wild pitch to plate Pitt's 10\nth\nand final run of the day.\nEddie Smink\nfinished off the Cardinal with a 1-2-3 ninth inning to complete his stellar outing and clinch Pitt's first ACC series of the season.\nThe Panthers return home this Wednesday, March 18 against Youngstown State at Charles L. Cost Field."
  },
